YtrzWnBBHws.title: Get PAID to EXPLORE MISSISSAUGA With the LOCAL GEMS PASS
YtrzWnBBHws.description:
What would you say if I told you that you could get PAID to explore a city? Well that's exactly what's happening in Mississauga with the Local Gems Pass. Visit iconic landmarks and discover some hidden gems as well! 

Simply sign up for a free pass at https://www.visitmississauga.ca/localgems, visit participating locations and businesses, and check-in at each new place.

Once you've visited 10 Local Gems, you'll receive a $25 prepaid Mastercard and if you visit them all, you'll get a $100 prepaid Mastercard. Pretty sweet!

#MississaugaLocalGems #VisitMississauga

ri9hRnVVD-I.title: INSIDE the NIAGARA PARKS POWER STATION + Evening Immersive Program
ri9hRnVVD-I.description:
Step inside Niagara Falls' newest attraction - the Niagara Parks Power Station. In this video, I give you a tour of the Niagara Parks Power Station plus showcase the evening immersive program - Currents: Niagara's Power Transformed.

Built in 1905 and decommissioned in 2006, it had undergone extensive renovations and restorations to reimagine the Niagara Parks Power Station into an educational and entertainment experience. 

Learn more and book tickets: https://www.niagaraparks.com/visit/attractions/niagara-parks-power-station

In partnership with Niagara Parks.

All drone footage courtesy of Niagara Parks.

i3pPP4CsQ7A.title: An Island Only Accessible During Low Tide -  Minister's Island | NEW BRUNSWICK
i3pPP4CsQ7A.description:
An island that's only accessible during low tide? Count me in! Minister's Island is located by St. Andrew's, New Brunswick and is a Provincial and National Historic Site. When the tide goes out, a sandbar appears, allowing visitors to drive right across the ocean floor to explore the island.


Home to 4 distinct groups of people - the Passamaquoddy Indigeneous Peoples, John Hanson & family, Reverend Samuel Andrews, and it's most notable inhabitant, Sir William Van Horne. He was the president of the Canadian National Railway and built his summer home on the island, plus a circular bathhouse, a large barn, and more. Check out the video to see what Minister's Island is all about!


Learn more: https://ministersisland.net



In partnership with Tourism New Brunswick: https://tourismnewbrunswick.ca/

2gPJe9M-1wM.title: Fundy Trail Parkway - The Ultimate Guide | NEW BRUNSWICK
2gPJe9M-1wM.description:
The Fundy Trail Parkway is a 30km parkway that runs right along the coast of the Bay of Fundy in New Brunswick's southern coast. The surrounding park and ecosystem is home a number of lookouts, observation decks, hiking trails, waterfalls, and more. There's so much to do along the Fundy Trail Parkway that you can easily spend a full day here. In this video I'm breaking down everything you can see and do along the Fundy Trail Parkway!

For more information, visit: https://www.fundytrailparkway.com
In partnership with Tourism New Brunswick: https://tourismnewbrunswick.ca/


Subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca



*Please note: drone footage was captured with permission. Drone use is otherwise not permitted in the park*

UsRwDwtYe4c.title: ST ANDREWS, NEW BRUNSWICK - ULTIMATE VISITORS GUIDE
UsRwDwtYe4c.description:
Your ultimate guide to St Andrews, New Brunswick. Located in the southwestern corner of New Brunswick, St. Andrews is one of the province’s premier seaside destinations. It was established by the United Empire Loyalists in 1783, and by the 1800s it was one of the region’s largest seaports. The early 1900s saw a shift towards tourism, drawing summer vacationers from Montreal and Boston and today St. Andrews has solidified itself as one of the best seaside destinations in Canada. 

Often referred to as St Andrews By-the-Sea, the town was designated a National Historic District in 1998. It’s a wonderful blend of old and new. Its history is proudly on display and you’ll find all the amenities summer vacationers look for in a destination.

In partnership with Destination New Brunswick: https://tourismnewbrunswick.ca/

✶ FEATURING ✶

◆ Kingsbrae Garden
◆ Huntsman Marine Science Centre / Fundy Discovery Aquarium
◆ Historic Water Street
◆ Katy's Cove Beach
◆ Minister's Island
◆ The Algonquin Resort
◆ Algonquin Golf Course
◆ Van Horne Trail

y21W35dU-fE.title: MIDDLESEX COUNTY WEEKEND ITINERARY | ONTARIO TRAVELS
y21W35dU-fE.description:
Enjoy the ultimate getaway to Middlesex County with this 2-day weekend itinerary! Located in the heart of Ontario’s Southwest, Middlesex County is comprised of 8 townships with a combined total population of about 75,000 people. The region is known for its rich history, fertile farmland, and diverse communities. For this edition of my Small Town Getaways, we’ll be travelling to a few different spots in Middlesex County

-nM7-y7hUPw.title: PORT BURWELL WEEKEND ITINERARY | ONTARIO TRAVELS
-nM7-y7hUPw.description:
For the ultimate getaway to Port Burwell, Ontario, follow this 2-day weekend itinerary! Subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca

Port Burwell was once a busy harbour town known for its shipbuilding, fisheries, exports of lumber, and the entry point for coal shipped across Lake Erie from Pennsylvania.

Today, Port Burwell is a hidden gem in Elgin County and has become a frequented destination for beach goers and adventurers during the peak summer months. The town is completely walkable and only has a permanent population of about 1,000 people. But with attractions like a Cold War submarine, a historic lighthouse, and a Blue Flag beach, Port Burwell makes for a relaxing and enjoyable weekend getaway.

In partnership with Ontario's Southwest https://www.ontariossouthwest.com/ and Elgin County Tourism https://www.elgintourist.com/

✶NOTE✶ This video was filmed in 2019. Please double check with all establishments for the latest service levels and offerings, and follow all local health guidelines when visiting.

-----------------------------------------------
✶ FEATURED IN THIS VIDEO ✶

◆ Port Burwell Historic Lighthouse and Museum
◆ Aunt Tammy’s Off the Hook Restaurant
◆ Otter Be Here - Kayaking
◆ Grey Gables B&B
◆ Izzy's Schooners Restaurant & Patio Lookout
◆ HMCS Ojibwa
◆ Simply Scoops Ice Cream & Eatery
◆ Port Burwell Beach

EKMRZz-HTzg.title: WEEKEND ITINERARY in ERIEAU, ONTARIO!
EKMRZz-HTzg.description:
For the ultimate getaway to Erieau, Ontario, check out this 2-day itinerary! Located just over an hours’ drive from either Windsor or London, Ontario, Erieau is a small peninsular town in the Chatham-Kent region. Situated on the north shores of Lake Erie,it boasts some of the warmest waters on the lake, and is a popular destination amongst beach goers and fishing enthusiasts. Affectionately called “the Village”, this charming small town sees visitors return year after year. and whether you’re looking to spend time on the water, biking the trails, or just relaxing at the beach, Erieau is a beloved spot, perfect for a weekend getaway.

In partnership with Ontario's Southwest https://www.ontariossouthwest.com/ and Visit Chatham-Kent https://visitck.ca/

✶NOTE✶ This video was filmed in 2019. Please double check with all establishments for the latest service levels and offerings, and follow all local health-guides when visiting.

-----------------------------------------------

◆ Bayside Brewing
◆ The Gift Cabin
◆ Erie-O Motel
◆ Molly & OJ's

fPLhTKwSwY8.title: TOP 10 THINGS TO DO IN ATLANTIC CANADA
fPLhTKwSwY8.description:
Welcome to Atlantic Canada! Featuring the provinces of New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, and Newfoundland and Labrador, this region is filled with history, gorgeous landscapes, the freshest seafood in the country, and the most friendly people you’ll find in Canada. It's the perfect region to road trip. To get the most out of your visit, here are the top 10 things to do in Atlantic Canada!


*Note: all footage was filmed before the pandemic.


Subscribe for more great travel content: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca


Featuring:
The Beaches of Prince Edward Island
The Fortress of Louisbourg
Charlottetown, Prince Edward Island
The Bay of Fundy and the Hopewell Rocks
Peggy's Cove
Halifax, Nova Scotia
St John's, Newfoundland and Labrador
Gros Morne National Park
Indulge in the Seafood
The Cabot Trail

BV4q6fYGxJk.title: SeeYouSoon Travel - Channel Trailer!
BV4q6fYGxJk.description:
Welcome to SeeYouSoon Travel! 


My name is Arienne, and I’m an award-winning travel videographer, photographer and blogger from Toronto. For over a decade, I’ve been creating video and digital media content that features destinations around the world. From local to global, coast to coast and anywhere in between, I’m excited to share with you what’s beyond your front door.

I have an insatiable curiosity to learn about different cultures first hand and a willingness to jump into activities that’ll get your heart rate going. 

On this channel, you’ll find videos that highlight cities, the outdoors, festivals and cultural events, and of course, food and drinks. I shoot, edit and host all my videos. I’m kind of a one-woman show.

My goal through this channel is to leave you feeling either inspired, informed or simply entertained. So, hit that subscribe button, click that notification bell and come along for the ride. And with that, as I like to say, we’ll see you soon.

-----------------------------------------------

8yzZ0G1NNdo.title: 5 EPIC THINGS TO DO in NIAGARA FALLS this FALL
8yzZ0G1NNdo.description:
Niagara Falls is Canada's most popular natural attraction, bringing in millions of visitors from all over the world each year. During the Fall season, the area is particularly beautiful when the changing colours on the leaves really make the landscape pop. There's quite a lot to do in Niagara Falls apart from seeing the Falls themselves, so in this video I'm showcasing 5 things you can do around Niagara Falls.


Special thanks to Niagara Parks for hosting me.

rqRtJwqo1kI.title: HOW TO MAKE KOREAN PAJEON (파전) PANCAKE | KOREAN CUISINE
rqRtJwqo1kI.description:
In this week's recipe video, I'm showing you how to make Korean Pajeon (파전). Pajeon is a savoury pancake usually enjoyed when it's raining. Koreans believe the sounds of rainfall are similar to pajeon cooking. There are many variations of pajeon (based on the types of ingredients used) but haemul pajeon, or seafood pancake remains the most popular kind. Subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca

✶Ingredients✶
Haemul Pajeon
◆ 1 cup Korean pancake mix
◆ 3/4 cup cold water
◆ 1.5 cups mixed seafood
◆ 1 tsp sesame oil
◆ 1 bunch green onions
◆ Korean red chili peppers to taste

Dipping Sauce
◆ 1 tbsp white vinegar
◆ 1 tbsp soy sauce
◆ 1 tbsp minced white onion
◆ 1 tsp granulated sugar
◆ 1 tsp sesame seeds
◆ pinch of dried red pepper flakes

Recipe makes two 8-inch pancakes.

RtL7pOwmvaE.title: KIMCHI JJIGAE RECIPE (김치찌개) | KOREAN CUISINE
RtL7pOwmvaE.description:
In this week's episode, I'm sharing a dish I make very often at home - Kimchi Jjigae (김치찌개)! Kimchi Jjigae, or Kimchi Stew, is widely popular in Korea. It's made with kimchi, fermented cabbage in a red pepper paste, and served alongside a bowl of rice. Korean's love this dish so much, they'll usually eat it at least once or twice a week.


✶Ingredients✶
◆ 1/2 white onion, sliced
◆ 1 clove garlic, minced
◆ 1 cup pork belly (samgyeopsal), thick-cut bacon also works*
◆ 2 cups kimchi
◆ 1 tbsp sesame oil
◆ 1 herb or vegetable bouillon cube
◆ 1 tbsp soy sauce
◆ 1 tbsp brown sugar
◆ 1/2 - 1 tbsp gochujang (red pepper paste)
◆ 2 stalks green onion, chopped


Recipe makes 2 servings.


* you can substitute pork belly with a can of tuna, diced tofu, or protein of your choice.

d7z-EZCBKOY.title: HOW TO MAKE AUTHENTIC PAD THAI (ผัดไทย)
d7z-EZCBKOY.description:
In this video I'm showing you how to make Thailand's most popular noodle dish, Pad Thai (ผัดไทย)! Once you've done this easy-to-follow recipe a couple of times, you won't need to order pad thai again!

Ingredients for 1 serving of Pad Thai

◆ 1 egg
◆ 1 tbsp small dried shrimp
◆ 1/3 cup diced firm tofu
◆ 8 pieces raw shrimp (or protein of choice)
◆ 1.5 cups of thin rice noodles
◆ 1 cup bean sprouts
◆ 3 tbsp tamarind water (recipe below)
◆ 2 tbsp palm sugar simple syrup (recipe below)
◆ 1.5 tbsp fish sauce
◆ 1/3 cup chopped green onion
◆chopped peanuts and lime wedge to garnish

If cooking multiple servings of Pad Thai, make sure to cook them in batches (and not all at once).

✶Tamarind Water Recipe✶
◆ 4oz tamarind paste
◆ 3.5 cups of water

Combine tamarind paste and water in a pot and bring to a boil. Once the water begins to boil, reduce heat to low and let simmer for 15-20 minutes (stir mixture periodically to break up the tamarind paste). Then turn off the heat and let the pot sit on the stove top for 30 minutes. Once the mixture has cooled, strained out the paste using a cheesecloth or a coffee filter so you're left with just the liquid. Store liquid in an airtight container for 3-4 days in the refrigerator or freeze in ice cubes trays and store in the freezer for up to 6 months.


✶Palm Sugar Simple Syrup Recipe✶
◆ 3oz palm sugar
◆ 1/3 cup water

In a small pot set to medium heat, combine the palm sugar and water. As the water heats up, break up the palm sugar to help it dissolve. Heat up the mixture until the sugar has fully dissolved, making sure not to let it boil. Once the palm sugar has dissolved, turn off the heat and let the mixture cool. You can store this in an airtight container for about 2 weeks.

localized.description:
In this video I'm showing you how to make Thailand's most popular noodle dish, Pad Thai (ผัดไทย)! Once you've done this easy-to-follow recipe a couple of times, you won't need to order pad thai again!

Ingredients for 1 serving of Pad Thai

◆ 1 egg
◆ 1 tbsp small dried shrimp
◆ 1/3 cup diced firm tofu
◆ 8 pieces raw shrimp (or protein of choice)
◆ 1.5 cups of thin rice noodles
◆ 1 cup bean sprouts
◆ 3 tbsp tamarind water (recipe below)
◆ 2 tbsp palm sugar simple syrup (recipe below)
◆ 1.5 tbsp fish sauce
◆ 1/3 cup chopped green onion
◆chopped peanuts and lime wedge to garnish

If cooking multiple servings of Pad Thai, make sure to cook them in batches (and not all at once).

✶Tamarind Water Recipe✶
◆ 4oz tamarind paste
◆ 3.5 cups of water

Combine tamarind paste and water in a pot and bring to a boil. Once the water begins to boil, reduce heat to low and let simmer for 15-20 minutes (stir mixture periodically to break up the tamarind paste). Then turn off the heat and let the pot sit on the stove top for 30 minutes. Once the mixture has cooled, strained out the paste using a cheesecloth or a coffee filter so you're left with just the liquid. Store liquid in an airtight container for 3-4 days in the refrigerator or freeze in ice cubes trays and store in the freezer for up to 6 months.


✶Palm Sugar Simple Syrup Recipe✶
◆ 3oz palm sugar
◆ 1/3 cup water

In a small pot set to medium heat, combine the palm sugar and water. As the water heats up, break up the palm sugar to help it dissolve. Heat up the mixture until the sugar has fully dissolved, making sure not to let it boil. Once the palm sugar has dissolved, turn off the heat and let the mixture cool. You can store this in an airtight container for about 2 weeks.

OLgMxrKpmRs.title: HOW TO MAKE THAI PAPAYA SALAD (SOM TAM ส้มตำ)
OLgMxrKpmRs.description:
In this series, I'm sharing recipes inspired by my travels! Learn how to make authentic Thai papaya salad (som tam ส้มตำ) in this easy to follow video.


Ingredients for 1 Serving of Papaya Salad:
1tbsp palm sugar
1 clove of garlic
4 small pieces of lime

Thai red chili to taste
1tbsp small dried shrimp
1/3 cup long beans
juice from half a lime
1tbsp tamarind water*
1tbsp fish sauce
1.5 cups of green papaya (in long, thin strips)
0.5 cups of carrots (in long, thin strips)
6 cherry tomatoes (halved)
chopped peanuts to taste


Prepare each serving of papaya salad separately for the best results.


*Tamarind Water Recipe*
4oz tamarind paste
3.5 cups of water


Combine tamarind paste and water in a pot and bring to a boil. Once the water begins to boil, reduce heat to low and let simmer for 15-20 minutes (stir mixture periodically to break up the tamarind paste). Then turn off the heat and let the pot sit on the stovetop for 30 minutes. Once the mixture has cooled, strained out the paste using a cheesecloth or a coffee filter so you're left with just the liquid. Store liquid in an airtight container for 3-4 days in the refrigerator or freeze in ice cubes trays and store in the freezer for up to 6 months.

RQbjsd3c1Z4.title: WEEKEND ITINERARY in CHATHAM, ONTARIO!
RQbjsd3c1Z4.description:
Plan the ultimate weekend getaway to Chatham, Ontario with this 2-day itinerary! Located about halfway between Windsor and London, Ontario, Chatham is a riverfront community in the Chatham-Kent region. Known for its rich history, classic cars and fertile land, the region was also an important destination point along the underground railroad. 

Today, Chatham has become a cultural hub of arts and entertainment and is experiencing a renaissance thanks in part to unique and trendy businesses opening across town.

PRyhtVJ8xqA.description:
Plan the ultimate weekend getaway to Caledonia, Ontario with this 2-day itinerary! Located in Haldimand County, just 15 minutes outside Hamilton, Ontario, Caledonia is a pictueraque community along the Canadian Heritage Grand River. There’s historic sites, green spaces, outdoor activities, and delicious eats to keep the whole family entertained for a weekend getaway

FujaD752dco.title: WEEKEND ITINERARY in ST. THOMAS, ONTARIO!
FujaD752dco.description:
Plan the ultimate weekend getaway to St. Thomas, Ontario with this 2-day itinerary! Located about a 20-minute drive south of London, Ontario, St. Thomas was founded in 1881 and was an important railway junction. Its location made it the primary stop along the Canadian shortcut between Detroit and Buffalo, and grew to see 26 railways pass through during the 19th and 20th century, thus earning the name Railway Capital of Canada. 

Today, the trains no longer pass through St. Thomas but its railway heritage is woven into the culture of the city and is proudly on display. From historic buildings to green spaces, friends, families, and especially railway aficionados will all enjoy a weekend visit.

In partnership with Ontario's Southwest https://www.ontariossouthwest.com/ and Railway City Tourism https://www.railwaycitytourism.com.
-----------------------------------------------
Featured in this video:

Canadian Southern Railway Station (CASO Station)
Elgin County Railway Museum
Bella Jacks
St. Thomas Elevated Park
Seed Confections
The Comfort Inn
Railway City Brewing
Rail City Bistro
Streamliners Espresso Bar
Pinafore Park
Caps Off Brewery

R8eAkKiz80w.title: The Oxford County Cheese Trail | Culinary Trails in Ontario's Southwest
R8eAkKiz80w.description:
In this video series, I'm travelling around Ontario's Southwest to find some of the best Culinary Trails this region has to offer. 

This episode, I'm featuring The Oxford County Cheese Trail. This culinary trail is made up of 24 stops and includes cheese makers, restaurants and local businesses all using cheese and milk products produced in the region. With so many stops, you'll have to make multiple visits to the region, so I've put together a weekend getaway itinerary for some of the best stops along the trail.

Learn more about The Oxford County Cheese Trail here: https://www.tourismoxford.ca/listing.aspx?categoryid=723 

In Partnership With: Ontario's Southwest Tourism: https://www.ontariossouthwest.com/ TWEPI: https://visitwindsoressex.com/

E-9LvgpBLhw.title: Eat, Drink, Dine Kingsville | Culinary Trails in Ontario's Southwest
E-9LvgpBLhw.description:
In this video series, I'm travelling around Ontario's Southwest to find some of the best Culinary Trails this region has to offer. 

This episode, I'm featuring Eat, Drink, Dine Kingsville. Located along the north shores of Lake Erie, the town of Kingsville has developed into quite the culinary scene. Eat, Drink, Dine Kingsville is a group of restaurants and food establishments all working together to promote the culinary offerings in the area and this video showcases the members of the group.

Learn more about Eat, Drink, Dine Kingsville here: http://www.eatdrinkdinekingsville.ca/

upX0iJB5InQ.title: CRAFT BREWERIES & DISTILLERIES in WINDSOR ESSEX  | Culinary Trails in Ontario's Southwest
upX0iJB5InQ.description:
In this video series, I'm travelling around Ontario's Southwest to find some of the best Culinary Trails this region has to offer. 

This episode I'm showcasing the Barrels, Bottles and Brews Trails located in the Windsor Essex County Pelee Island region. It's made up of 11 stops and gives you the chance to learn about the history of Canadian whisky and sample some delicious craft beer.

Learn more about the Barrels, Bottles and Brews Trails here: http://www.barrelsbottlesbrews.ca/

-LjZ0-blNho.title: HALIFAX'S PIER 21 and MY FAMILY'S IMMIGRATION STORY | NOVA SCOTIA
-LjZ0-blNho.description:
I visit the Canadian Museum of Immigration at Pier 21 in Halifax, Nova Scotia to retrace my family's arrival to Canada. My grandparents first set foot on Canadian soil at Pier 21 and I hope to find information about their arrival and their immigration experience.

Between 1928 and 1971, close to 1 million people came through Pier 21. It played a crucial role during WWII and the post-war years for both immigrants and the Canadian military. 1 in 5 Canadians began their new life in Canada at Pier 21, and today you can visit the Canadian National Immigration Museum of Pier 21 to learn about their immigration story.

Learn More: https://pier21.ca

wAXWX93Cq9w.title: ATLANTIC CANADA ROADTRIP MONTAGE VIDEO!
wAXWX93Cq9w.description:
2 months, 4 provinces, and close to 13,000kms later, all condensed into one epic 3-minute montage video. Check out our incredible roadtrip through Atlantic Canada!! Read more about our roadtrip: http://bit.ly/RoadtripNumbers

Subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca

After years of traveling to many parts of the globe, I finally made the decision to start exploring my own country. Tristan and I saved up for over a year to make this roadtrip a reality and it surpassed our wildest imaginations. We visited all 4 Atlantic Canada provinces, including New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, Prince Edward Island, and even Newfoundland and Labrador.

Atlantic Canada is truly a special place in the country. The landscape, the history, and the people make this the best region in Canada to explore by car. You'll be captivated by the scenery and get hooked by its charm.
-----------------------------------------------

A special thank you to Tourism New Brunswick, Visit Nova Scotia, and Parks Canada for their assistance for parts of our trip.

*Note: all drone videography within Parks Canada National Parks and Historic Sites were captured with permission. Drone use in National Parks and Historic Sites are otherwise forbidden.

oJbuf09rYkE.title: INSIDE the LUDWIGSBURG RESIDENTIAL PALACE | GERMANY
oJbuf09rYkE.description:
The Ludwigsburg Residential Palace is one of the largest baroque-style buildings to survive in it's original condition in Europe! This is where the kings and dukes of the Baden-Württemberg region lived before they moved the Palace to Stuttgart. It was built in 1704 and features 452 rooms across 18 buildings in both baroque and classical architectural and decorative styles.  

I got a private tour of the Ludwigsburg Residential Palace and I'm taking you inside!

Don't forget to subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca

For more about the Ludwigsburg Residential Palace check out: http://www.schloss-ludwigsburg.de/en/home/

1UwBqnStoAg.title: THE FORTRESS OF LOUISBOURG BY DAY and NIGHT | NOVA SCOTIA
1UwBqnStoAg.description:
Welcome to the Fortress of Louisbourg in Louisbourg, Nova Scotia! It was founded in 1713 by the French and is the largest reconstructed historic site in North America. Come see what it's like to explore this living museum including becoming a soldier and sleeping overnight in a traditional 18th Century style tent!

Subscribe: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca 

Read more about the experience on the blog: http://seeyousoon.ca/video-the-fortress-of-louisbourg-nova-scotia/
-----------------------------------------------

Located on the southeastern coast of Nova Scotia’s Cape Breton Island, the Fortress of Louisbourg was one of the busiest seaports in North America during the mid-18th century. It was built to protect and provide a base for France's lucrative North American fishing industry and also to protect Quebec City from British invasions. But it fell under siege twice to the British before being demolished in the 1760s.

Fast forward to 1961 where the Government of Canada began reconstructing the fortress. Today, one quarter of the fortress has been reconstructed, using some of the original stonework, and includes about 40 buildings over an area of 5 hectares.

The Fortress of Louisbourg is a living museum. Visitors can get a sense of what life was like in the fortress by interacting with individuals living a typical day in the 18th century. Visitors can wander through the streets, step inside houses and shops, and even grab a meal at one of two restaurants. You can also learn about the history of rum and sample the Fortress Rum, aged in barrels on-site.

Daily activities include guided tours, dance performances, military drills and learning what life was like for a soldier. Your time at the Louisbourg Fortress can be as immersive as you want, so naturally, I dove right in and reported for duty. 

The most unique aspect of your visit to the Louisbourg Fortress is that your time doesn’t have to end when the gates close at 5pm. You can actually stay overnight in the fortress. One option is sleeping in the Rodrigue House. It’s located right in the heart of the fortress and comes with straw-beds and a roof overhead.

Another option is to sleep in an 18th-century style tent within the walls of the King’s Bastion. Everything is provided for, including sleeping pads and cooking supplies. All you need to bring is a sleeping bag, pillow, and any food you want to eat.

As the last of the day’s visitors made their exit, Tristan and I got settled in to what would be our home for the night.
-----------------------------------------------
Special thank you to Parks Canada for a fantastic visit!

Note: the use of drones is prohibited at the Fortress of Louisbourg. All drone videography was captured with special permission from Parks Canada and the Fortress of Louisbourg.
-----------------------------------------------

5lsqaT-ZVCY.title: THE HOPEWELL ROCKS - NEW BRUNSWICK | CANADA
5lsqaT-ZVCY.description:
Spending an epic day at Hopewell Rocks Provincial Park checking out the iconic Hopewell Rocks! Located along the Bay of Fundy in the Canadian province of New Brunswick, you can witness the greatest tidal shift in the world here. Tides change between 11-16metres every 12 hours! During low tide you can walk right on the ocean floor and during high tide you can kayak right through the famous Flower Pot Rocks.

Subscribe for more great travel videos: http://www.youtube.com/seeyousoonca

Plan your visit: http://www.thehopewellrocks.ca/
Kayaking provided by Baymount Outdoor Adventures: http://www.baymountadventures.com/

**Note: drone footage was captured with special permission from Hopewell Rocks Provincial Park. Drone use is otherwise forbidden.
---------------------------------------------

Our visit to Hopewell Rocks Provincial Park was part of a 2-month Atlantic Canada Roadtrip. Check out some of our other videos:

Adventure at Cape Enrage: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gn_xMYwMwd8
The Acadian Historical Village: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JkqiOrqBDHo&t=92s
Reversing Falls in Saint John: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gzfOQM2WAd4
Mount Carleton Provincial Park: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wcpSXFYuWOE

QduPr9DY_Dg.title: FOODS TO EAT AT A GERMAN CHRISTMAS MARKET!
QduPr9DY_Dg.description:
The best thing to do at a Christmas market in Germany is to eat your way through them! Check out all the must-eat foods and make sure to arrive hungry! Subscribe: http://youtube.com/seeyousoonca


Filmed in Aachen, Heidelberg, Koblenz, and Marburg, Germany.

 -----------------------------------------------
Foods Featured:
*Krakauer
*Bratwurst
*Half-metre sausage
*Mutzbraten - rotisserie pork
*Currywurst
*Sauerbraten - beef stew
*Pomme Frites - Belgian-style fries with mayo
*Reibekuchen - potato pancakes
*Fried mushrooms
*Maroni - roasted chestnuts
*Gebrannte Mandels - candied almonds
*Nougat
*Chocolate-covered fruit
*Marzipan
*Schneballen - pastry ball
*Waffles
*Pannfkuchen - crepes
*Germknodel - dessert dumpling
*Gluhwein - mulled wine
*Feuerzangenbowle - mulled wine with burnt rum

gzfOQM2WAd4.title: REVERSING FALLS in SAINT JOHN - DJI PHANTOM 4
gzfOQM2WAd4.description:
The Reversing Falls in Saint John, New Brunswick are a natural phenomenon. Located where the St. John River spills out into the Bay of Fundy, these falls get their name from a phenomenon that makes it appear as though the river is flowing in reverse. During low tide, the river empties into the Bay of Fundy, resulting in a series of rapids and whirlpools. As the tide rises, the bay fills up, reversing the flow of the water. 

Read about more things to do in Saint John on the blog: http:bit.ly/SaintJohnToDo

JkqiOrqBDHo.title: The Acadian Historical Village | New Brunswick
JkqiOrqBDHo.description:
The Acadian Historical Village in New Brunswick is a living museum dedicated to showcasing the life of the Acadians during the 1800 and 1900s. The village is comprised of original houses and buildings dating as far back as 1770. Visitors can explore the Acadian Historical Village by following a 2.5km walking path. Inside each of the buildings are interpreters, dressed from the time period, and carrying out traditional duties. Give yourself a minimum of 4 hours to completely explore the village.
-------------------------------------------------------------
For More Information: http://villagehistoriqueacadien.com/en

06LhVejcYPg.title: INSIDE the ICE HOTEL in QUEBEC CITY!
06LhVejcYPg.description:
Step inside North America's only Ice hotel! The Hotel de Glace in Quebec City is built every year using 30,000 tons of man-made snow and 500 tons of ice. It takes about 6 weeks to build and every year the hotel takes on a new theme. If you're really feeling adventurous, you can spend the night, but visitors can come and explore the hotel throughout the day. Don't leave without visiting the bar and grabbing a drink in a glass made entirely out of ice!

Subscribe for more great travel videos: https://youtube.com/seeyousoonca

For more information about this experience, read the blog post: http://www.seeyousoon.ca/video-inside-the-hotel-de-glace/
The Hotel de Glace: http://www.hoteldeglace-canada.com/

PkoEu3XaNZM.title: WINTER VIDEO SERIES: Snowshoeing Amongst 20,000 Sugar Maple Trees!
PkoEu3XaNZM.description:
It's the final part of my Winter Adventure Video Series in Ontario's Highlands! This week, we're slowing things down with snowshoeing at Wheelers Pancake House and Sugar Camp. They're one of the largest maple syrup producers in Ontario and have 20,000 tapped sugar maple trees! Subscribe to stay up to date with latest adventures: https://www.youtube.com/seeyousoonca

For more information about this experience, read the blog post: http://seeyousoon.ca/video-snowshoeing-at-wheelers-maple/

Also in this series:
-Snowmobiling for the First Time: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qa51X...
-Ice Climbing in Haliburton Highlands: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sTnVk...
-Skiing at Calabogie Peaks:https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bXLFd...

Ontario's Highlands is located north of Toronto and west of Ottawa. It's made up of 6 smaller regions and has so much to offer for all types of travelers.

Joining me in this video series is my friend Solmaz, aka The Curious Creature. Follow her adventures: http://www.thecuriouscreature.com

1hMhXOrI-Nw.description:
It's the final day on the Lemosho Route of Kilimanjaro! We give our thanks to the porters and guides and make the descent to the exit gate. The team tries to describe the entire experience in one word.

For more about this experience, visit the blog: www.seeyousoon.ca/video-kilimanjaro-lemo­sho-route-day-8/

Day 4 climbing Kilimanjaro's Lemosho Route is the 2nd hardest day (after summit day). We climbed to 15,000 feet up to Lava Tower and came across some interesting looking trees. 8-episode Kilimanjaro video series continues every Wednesday at 7pm EST! Subscribe: www.youtube.com/seeyousoonca.

For more about this experience, visit the blog: www.seeyousoon.ca/video-kilimanjaro-lemo­sho-route-day-4/

This video was filmed during a World Vision Canada charity climb to raise funds and awareness for their No Child For Sale campaign. The climb raised $143,340!! Thank you to everyone who donated to the cause! Follow on social media: #kiliclimb4kids

3Oz-V2aD4e4.title: Orangutans and the Matang Wildlife Centre
3Oz-V2aD4e4.description:
The Matang Wildlife Centre in Sarawak, Malaysia is dedicated to the care and rehabilitation of orangutans. Their core belief is that every animal has the chance to be released back into the wild. On a recent visit to the centre, I got the chance to see and experience the day-to-day tasks required to care for the animals with their Heart2Heart With Orangutan volunteer program.

For more information about this video, check out my blog post: http://seeyousoon.ca/orangutans-matang-wildlife-centre-sarawak/

To see what other conversation projects the Matang Wildlife Centre is involved with, visit: www.sarawakforestry.com

wt_PJogGscs.title: GoPro Hero 3 Home Renovation Timelapse
wt_PJogGscs.description:
Renovating your home takes a lot of work, especially if you take on most of the work yourself. What we thought would only take us a few weeks to complete, turned into 4 months. Through a lot of sweat, some blood, and maybe a few tears, we're so proud of the finished results and finally have a place to call home! 

I should note that although it may appear as if I did most of the work, the truth is that the husband helped out equally, he just forgot to turn on the camera every time he was working on our condo without me ;p

Captured with the GoPro Hero 3, Black Edition.

Music By: Klingande 'Punga'

When I'm not taking on DIY projects, I'm usually travelling and blogging about it.

BGM8APNHkQs.title: How to Cross the Streets in Vietnam
BGM8APNHkQs.description: Over 4 million motorbikes (and counting!) cram the roadways everyday in Ho Chi Minh City (Saigon). Being a pedestrian can be quite a challenge and seem down-right scary to new visitors. But the key to crossing the streets in Vietnam is to go slowly. Believe it or not, the motorcycles and cars will swerve around you. Check out the video to see a first-person's perspective of crossing the street in Vietnam.
